      <Text>
        <Sent id="3.1">&amp;gt; First define disability. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.2">&amp;gt; IMO, before you can define Accessibility you must first define disability. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.3">OK. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.4">Here's my short definition: </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.5">&amp;quot;Disability is a design flaw in the environment.&amp;quot; </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.6">Here's the long version, from a chapter in an upcoming book on web-based training: </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.7">&amp;quot;People are not &amp;quot;disabled.&amp;quot; </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.8">A disability is a consequence of design flaws in the environment. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.9">Some individuals, due to accident, illness, or heredity, have difficulties performing -- or cannot perform -- certain tasks, such as moving their legs, seeing, hearing, talking, grasping or lifting. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.10">When these functional limitations are severe enough to adversely affect a person's performance, and the natural and human environments fail to accommodate their functional limitations, the individual is said to have a disability.&amp;quot; </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.11">You take your pick. </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.12">If I were rewriting it, I would say something like this: </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.13">... ALL individuals, due to circumstance, accident, illness, or heredity, have difficulties performing -- or cannot perform -- certain tasks... </Sent>
        <Sent id="3.14">Alan </Sent>
