        <Sent id="4.1">&amp;gt; OK. </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.2">&amp;gt; Here's my short definition: </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.3">&amp;gt; &amp;quot;Disability is a design flaw in the environment.&amp;quot; </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.4">I like to tell people that if a blind person can't access the web page she's trying to use, the REASON is not _her_ disability, but the disability of the _web author_ who created the page. </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.5">That web author is &amp;quot;disabled&amp;quot; because he was _not able_ to make a correct web page. </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.6">Why should she suffer for _his_ problem or failing? </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.7">In no way is a user with a disability &amp;quot;disabled&amp;quot; on the web </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.8">-- the sites THEMSELVES have the disability inherent in their code by not being accessible! </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.9">We should identify the problem where it exists. </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.10">The problem is not that there's anything &amp;quot;wrong with&amp;quot; the user, it is a problem with the page author and his output! </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.11">-- </Sent>
        <Sent id="4.12">Kynn Bartlett mailto:kynn@hwg.org </Sent>
